Is Mrs. Meyer’s sustainable or is it greenwashing?

One year ago I said it was greenwashing, so let’s see if anything has changed…

Welcome to “sustainable or greenwashing month” where everyday leading up to Earth Month I’m sharing if brands and products are actually what they say they are.

Now I always thought this was a cleaner, greener brand, bc when you look at the packaging things look promising.

Let’s start with the positives. All products are leaping bunny certified cruelty free & I appreciate how you can look up each ingredient online and see specifically what it’s used for. Their palm oil is sustainably sourced by Roundtable on Sustainable Palm Oil (RSPO). & the down the drain products meet the European OECD standards for biodegradability. Some, but not all, products manufactured in a LEED-platinum certified factory & they offer a line of products which goes towards turning vacant lots into green spaces.

More recently they’ve launched concentrates and refills, which you guys know I love to see!!

HOWEVER, they are owned by the SC Johnson company which isn’t always a good sign. They don’t have much information regarding their ingredient sourcing and use a LOT of vague terms to describe their sustainability efforts with zero information to back their claims.

Mrs. Meyer’s was founded to basically make cleaning supplies smell good. The grandma it was based on was a big gardener which is why they’re all green and garden-y scented.

SO, for a popular brand that would have the money and resources to do better - I’m disappointed. They definitely have more information on their website than they did previously, but not enough to change my mind.

Seems like greenwashing to me - but what do you think? This month we’re doing an ENTIRE month of Sustainable or Greenwashing videos, so if there is a brand you want to see, stick around because it’s probably coming.

Is Dropps sustainable or is it greenwashing? 

Welcome to “sustainable or greenwashing month” where everyday leading up to Earth Month I’ve been sharing if brands and products are actually what they say they are. ‍

Dropps was founded to take the plastic packaging out of laundry detergent.

They’re a B-Corp, vegan, they source sustainable palm oil, and are currently working on getting their USDA biobased preferred certification. 

Sticking true to their mission of having plastic free packaging, their boxes are made of 100% recycled content and are completely plastic free.

For labor and manufacturing, Dropps shares some information in their 2022 impact reports regarding fair wages and compensation. Also in the report is a LOT more detailed information on their initiatives, like their partnership with nonprofit Oceana which helps with ocean conservation and their donations of excess product to nonprofits.

BUT, let’s about the elephant in the room - the pods. Pods are traditionally made with Polyvinyl Alcohol (PVA) which is a water soluble component, but generally people consider PVA a type of plastic. Because of that, it has a controversial background. Obviously we don’t want PVA in our waterways, and not all water facility treatment plants are able to filter PVA which was researched in *this study. It’s a sticky subject, but after going down a rabbit hole I found that often times this pod coating will end up becoming a sort of sludge which has to be scraped from water facility treatment plants and thrown away anyways. 

SO with that being said, I do think Dropps is a better option than traditional pods and I like their efforts, BUT depending on your stance on PVAs, they may not be the best option for you. I don’t think they’re greenwashing, and overall I would say the brand itself is pretty sustainable to me. 

This month I’ve done an ENTIRE month of Sustainable or Greenwashing videos, which you can binge watch on my page, but stick around because I’ll still be doing more throughout the year, and our next series is all about about living eco on a budget!

The sad reality of salmon runs in California where salmon habitat is blocked by dams and requires fish ladders and hatcheries. The Klamath river is free once again after the Klamath dam removal project removed 4 dams that were blocking salmon spawning grounds and destroying the ecosystem. But the Klamath river dam removal project has also sparked a debate. Are dams truly green energy? Or are dams another modern example of blatant greenwashing? Every year California would see 100's thousands of chinook salmon, where they have 17 distinctive salmons runs in this state alone! Of which spring run chinook salmon face extinction from the PG&E hydroelectric canal breach, during the salmon run. And now because of dams stealing to much water fall run chinook salmon populations are crashing drastically. On the verge of extinction. Chinook salmon are a keystone species keep river and ocean ecosystems healthy and thriving. When you remove salmon the entire food chain disappears. If we want to save chinook salmon we must learn from what the indigenous Yurok tribe did with the Klamath river. Where salmon have already returned after a 100 years. You don't need more hatcheries. You don't need more dams. You need to remove dams from ancestral spawning grounds that salmon have used for thousands of years before dams. And we need to restore salmon habitat, to allow salmon to spawn in the wild. Not in a hatchery artificially. Native salmon want there land back. And we are running out of time. Save chinook salmon in California before it’s to late. Instagam @nuocmamafoods Thit Kho Tau Vietnamese/Braised pork with eggs 
Vietnamese traditional dish. An oldie but a goodie ❤️ Voiceover are for entertaining purposes 
Recipe:
•3-4 lbs of thick pork belly with skin or any cut you prefer. 
• 12 hard boiled eggs(more if prefer)
• 1 tablespoon chopped garlic 
• 2 tablespoon chopped shallots 
• 2 can of coco rico coconut soda ( optional, coconut water 7 up or coke cola. 
• 1 cup water 
• 1/2 cup fish sauce ( 3 crabs brand)
• 1/4 cup oyster sauce 
• 1/2 teaspoon ground pepper 
• 1 teaspoon garlic powder 
• 1 teaspoon onion powder 
• 1 teaspoon paprika 
• 1 teaspoon msg(optional)
Caramelized sauce:
• 1 tablespoon cooking oil 
• 2 tablespoon sugar 

 Cut your meat into cube. Wash and clean. Parboiled for 6-8 minutes with a tablespoon of salt.  Take meat out, clean and rinse.  Set aside.
 1•In a pot add oil and sugar. Wait for sugar to turn dark brown. Add garlic, and shallots. Sauté for 10-15 second. 
2•Add meat, stir to coated with the caramelize sauce. 
3.Add coconut soda, water, fish sauce, oyster sauce, ground pepper, paprika, garlic powder, onion powder and msg. 
4•Covered and bring to a boil. Scoop out the scums on top. Then cover and reduced heat to low. Simmer for 1 hrs. 
5•Uncovers and add in the hard boiled eggs . Continue to simmer for another 1/2 hrs. or until meat are tender. Flip eggs once in a while. 
6•Scoops out some of the oil on top. 
7•Taste and adjust. If meat needs to be more tender. Simmer a little longer. Enjoy

Acid-washed jeans became a major fashion trend in the 1980s, known for their distinctive, almost marble-like faded look. The technique involved washing jeans with chlorine and pumice stones, which created a mix of lighter and darker areas, giving them a bleached, vintage appearance. This style was synonymous with the rebellious and edgy vibe of the decade, often worn by rockstars and icons of the glam metal and punk scenes. The look was especially popularized by brands like Guess and Levi’s, and it quickly became a staple in both men’s and women’s fashion. Acid-washed jeans were typically paired with oversized denim jackets, graphic tees, neon accessories, and big hairstyles, making them a defining element of the 80s aesthetic. Their popularity extended into the early 90s but eventually faded as simpler, darker denim came back into vogue. However, acid-washed styles occasionally reemerge in modern fashion, often as a nostalgic throwback to the boldness of 80s culture.#acidwashed #jeans #1980s #80sfashion #throwback #nostalgia #retrofashion #fashiontiktok #denim #style #genx #80skids

Lamento decírtelo, pero puede que te estés autoengañando ¡sin saberlo!
.
Muy poca gente es consciente de esto (o no quiere serlo), pero no hay materiales buenos ni malos en sí, y la manera adecuada de evaluar cómo de ecológico es un producto es analizando todo su ciclo de vida (materia prima, fabricación, transporte, uso, fin de vida...) porque cada etapa tiene impactos ambientales
.
¿Y cómo se analiza?
.
✅ La ciencia cuenta con una herramienta analítica, metodológica y objetiva llamada Análisis del Ciclo de Vida, que contempla los impactos ambientales de un producto o servicio a lo largo de todo su ciclo de vida
.
✅ Hace especial hincapié en el balance de los materiales utilizados, la energía consumida y la contaminación generada. Se analizan impactos como cambio climático, reducción de la capa de ozono, toxicidad humana marina y terrestre, agotamiento de recursos energéticos, etc
.
✅ El ACV es fundamental para la ayuda en la toma de decisiones con rigor científico, escoger las mejores tecnologías disponibles y reducir los impactos ambientales desde su diseño
.
✅ Además sirve para comparar entre diferentes productos y poder elegir la opción ambientalmente mejor. También hay variaciones de esta herramienta para evaluar el aspecto Social y Económico
.
¿Por qué es importante el Análisis del Ciclo de Vida?
.
 Porque si solo se tiene en cuenta el material del que está fabricado un producto y se obvia el resto de impactos de las otras fases del ciclo de vida, se tendrá información sesgada y estaremos centrándonos en el árbol que nos impide ver el bosque
.
Es decir, que 1 producto puede ser más ecológico siendo de plástico, vidrio, metal... según que condiciones y factores
.

.

How to overdye jeans What happens when you put blue jeans in yellow dye? Give your jeans a refresh for Spring with this easy upcycle diy project! 1️⃣ Pre-wash jeans, and keep fabric damp. 2️⃣ Fill a large pot with hot water, 1 cup of salt, and 1 teaspoon of dish soap. There must be enough water to fully submerge the jeans and stir them easily. 3️⃣ Put on rubber gloves, and shake dye bottle well. Add half a bottle of Rit All Purpose Dye in Lemon Yellow to pot. 4️⃣ Place pot on stovetop, and set to medium heat. 5️⃣ Add jeans to dye bath. Stir jeans constantly for 30 minutes and make sure all areas of the fabric get submerged evenly. Use tongs to help separate any folds in the fabric. 6️⃣ To lock in your color and reduce bleeding, use RIT ColorStay Dye fixative. Fill a sink or bucket with 3 gallons of hot water and add half a bottle of the Dye Fixative. Move jeans immediately from the dye bath to the prepared Dye Fixative bath. Stir jeans for 20 minutes. 7️⃣ Rinse jeans in sink with cool water until water runs clear. 8️⃣ Wash jeans by hand or washing machine (by themselves) with mild detergent and warm water.  #ritdye #upcycle #thriftflip #fabricdyeing #reworkedclothing

Don’t fall for healthwashing! Find out how companies trick you into thinking products are healthy when they’re not.
#Healthwashing #KnowWhatYouEat #HealthyLiving #FoodLabels #NutritionTruth

Dont be fooled by creative marketing that certain items are healthy or better for you because of pretty pictures, or health-washing labels like “gluten-free” and “dairy-free” which don’t automatically make it healthier (there is absolutely a place for these with allergies, don’t get me wrong!) 

They can be great, but when you shop solely based on these labels, you can be easily tricked. 

Especially as a health coach but EVEN more as a pregnant new mom, I’m extra diligent about what food and drinks I’m consuming and the quality of what I put in my body. This doesn’t means its always perfect. (we like to ditch perfection over here!!) But knowing what I have in my house and pantry is majority whole foods, ingredients I know, minimal added sugars, without inflammatory oils, and organic as often as I can leaves me feeling confident in my health when I decide to stray for a special product, night out, or indulgence. 

Let’s instead make informed decisions & here are some of go to brands that I know, love, and trust for my body, baby’s health, and my clients.

Funny how the Conservative BC forest plan shares the same name of ‘Forestry for the Future’ with the widely prevalent greenwashing campaign from the Forest Products Association of Canada, or FPAC, an industry association representing the biggest pulp, paper, and timber companies in all of North America, both using vague language around forest stewardship that makes them sound like they’re radically progressive when the reality is far different from that. 

Forestry for the Future has been called out many times for their blatant greenwashing, including biased surveys and email campaigns that strategically limit options to prevent advocating for protection or other values being considered in forest management. While they claim to advocate for sustainable practices, the companies they represent (including Canfor, Interfor, West Fraser, Weyerhauser and Paper Excellence) all not only actively log old growth forests, but they are fiercely engaged in lobbying against any changes in policy, including continuing to clearcut log, keeping the annual allowable cut high, and preventing any sort of biodiversity or ecosystem values to be considering in harvest practices.

At the same time, they have been actively closing down operations throughout Canada while opening new ones elsewhere, scapegoating regulations, when in reality its because there simply isn’t enough timber as a result of their decades of over-harvesting and mismanagement. 

The Conservative platform is so deeply embedded in the pockets of the logging industry that they not only use the same tagline, but the same greenwashy language - heck, its probably all done by the same marketing firm!

The solutions to the issues we face in forestry from a lack of fibre, to job loss, to ecological mismanagement are NOT going to come from the same colonial capitalist companies solely operating for profits that created those problems in the first place.  We need to do things differently if we want to create a different, better future for all of us here today and those who follow, and if we keep letting the powerful industry players do the same thing they’ve always done, it’s only going to get worse.

Is Saltair sustainable or is it greenwashing?

Welcome to my series “sustainable or greenwashing month” where I’m sharing if brands and products are actually what they say they are. 

Y’all have requested Saltair, and I was intrigued since they come in cute aluminum packaging - so let’s dive in. ‍♀️

Saltair was founded by Iskra Lawrence, a brittish model who promotes body positivity.

Saltair products are vegan, paraben free, sulfate free, and I like how they have ingredient transparency on their website by breaking down why they use each one. They do claim to be cruelty free but I couldn’t find a third party verification, so just something to note.

Saltair partners with One Tree Planted and using mostly aluminum packaging which is infinitely recyclable which I love - but I couldn’t find much on their ingredient sourcing or manufacturing practices. 

I did find this (clip of website) on their website which is totally a start, I just wish they had more information available on what their company goals are when it comes to reducing their impact.

With that, Saltair defintiely has SOME sustainable initiatives, but they’re lacking the transparency I would need in order to say they’re a truly sustainable brand. SO, I hate to say it but it feels a little greenwashy to me.

I would only change my mind if they got a third party verification for being cruelty free & included tangible goals they’re working towards to be more eco consious - but what do you think? 

You can binge my other Sustainable or Greenwashing videos on my page AND also now on my website blog & if there is a brand you want to see, let me know in the comments!

Spring Deep Clean  Day 24/30: WASH WALLS (DOWNSTAIRS) The first time I washed my walls, I got a LOT of strong opinions.  Is it 1000% necessary….? Maybe not…. So why do I do it?! Here’s some reasons why! 1. **Maintain Cleanliness**: Walls can accumulate dust, dirt, fingerprints, and smudges over time, making your space look unkempt. Regular washing helps keep them clean and fresh. 2. **Improve Indoor Air Quality**: Dust and allergens can settle on walls and contribute to poor indoor air quality. Washing the walls can help reduce allergens and improve the overall air quality in your home. 3. **Prevent Mold and Mildew**: In areas with high humidity, such as kitchens and bathrooms, washing walls can help prevent the growth of mold and mildew, which can be harmful to health. 4. **Enhance Aesthetic Appeal**: Clean walls contribute to the overall aesthetics of a room. A fresh coat of paint or clean walls can make a space feel bright and inviting. (ESPECIALLY if you have white walls like me!) 5. **Extend the Life of Paint**: Regularly washing your walls can help preserve the finish of the paint, preventing it from fading or peeling prematurely. In summary, washing your walls not only enhances the appearance of your home but also contributes to a healthier and more pleasant living environment. I love using the @zepusa wall cleaner - BUT it does not work for flat paint!! If you have flat paint, use this ratio:  •1 part vinegar  •2 parts laundry detergent  •3 parts water  Ex: 1 tbsp vinegar, 2 tbsp laundry detergent, 3 tbsp water.  Also - use a wall mop! **Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl**

Get ready for a flavor explosion with this incredible Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl! Perfect for a cozy night in or impressing your guests, this dish is a vibrant and mouthwatering experience you won't forget.

**Ingredients:**

- 1 1/2 lbs chicken breast
- 3 cups flour
- Peanut oil (for frying)
- 1/2 cup corn starch
- 1 red bell pepper, diced
- 1 can of chickpeas, rinsed and drained
- 1 can of black beans, rinsed and drained
- 1 can of red kidney beans, rinsed and drained
- 1 red onion, finely diced
- 1 cucumber, diced (peeling is optional)
- 1 cup bulgur, cooked to perfection
- 1 cup couscous, cooked and fluffy
- Green onion for a fresh garnish
- Lime wedges for that zesty kick

**Hot Honey Sweet Chili Sauce:**

- 1 Tbsp minced garlic
- 2 Tbsp minced yellow onion
- 1/2 stick of unsalted butter
- 3 1/2 Tbsp raw honey
- 1/4 cup sweet chili sauce
- 3 Tbsp Frank’s Hot Sauce
- 1 Tbsp sriracha
- 1 tsp onion powder
- 1/2 tsp garlic powder
- 2 Tbsp rice wine vinegar
- Salt and pepper to taste

**Let’s Get Cooking!**

Kick things off by infusing your chicken breast with an array of vibrant flavors! Season it generously with chili powder, garlic powder, onion powder, paprika, cracked pepper, and a sprinkle of sea salt. A splash of avocado oil and a dollop of Greek yogurt will ensure your chicken stays juicy and delicious as it marinates in this flavor bomb!

Next, create a fabulous egg wash and mix your seasoned flour to coat that chicken. The flour should be a reflection of all those delectable spices we just added!

Heat that peanut oil to a sizzling 175 degrees Fahrenheit and watch the magic happen as you dredge your chicken in the egg wash, then in your seasoned flour before frying until it’s golden brown and perfectly crispy.

While the chicken is frying to perfection, let’s prep the colorful medley of beans and veggies! Open those cans, give them a rinse, and let them drain, then chop up that red bell pepper, red onion, cucumber, and get those vibrant green onions ready for garnish.

Now for the pièce de résistance: take those juicy, crispy chicken pieces and toss them in your homemade hot honey sauce! 

Assemble your bowl with layers of flavor, showcasing each ingredient beautifully. Finally, drizzle that mouthwatering hot honey sauce all over your creation, topping it off with a sprinkle of green onion and fresh lime wedges to elevate the taste and appeal.

Your sensational Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl is ready to devour! Enjoy every bite!                                                 #food #fyppppppppppppppppppppppp

#cocacola, #Danone và #Nestle vừa bị cáo buộc "#Greenwashing" vì tuyên bố chai nhựa của họ được tái chế 100%. Các khiếu nại pháp lý đã được Tổ chức Người tiêu dùng Châu Âu (BEUC), cùng sự hỗ trợ của các nhóm môi trường Client Earth và Liên minh Tiêu chuẩn Môi trường (Ecos) đưa lên Ủy ban Châu Âu. "Greenwashing" là thuật ngữ mà người ta dùng để nói đến việc "tẩy xanh" của các doanh nghiệp thông qua truyền thông tiếp thị đánh lừa người tiêu dùng tin rằng sản phẩm của họ thân thiện với môi trường.                VD như các thương hiệu vừa nêu, đã bị cáo buộc vì những tuyên bố về việc họ sử dụng chai nhựa 100% đã tái chế hoặc chai 100% có thể tái chế 100% trong hoạt động thương mại nhưng thực tế lại không như vậy. BEUC đã đệ đơn khiếu nại lên Ủy ban cũng như mạng lưới các cơ quan bảo vệ người tiêu dùng (CPC), kêu gọi mở một cuộc điều tra. Đại diện BEUC cho rằng, người tiêu dùng thì đang ngày càng có xu hướng đưa ra các lựa chọn bền vững, còn các thương hiệu thì luôn đưa ra những tuyên bố không chính xác và lừa đảo. Luật sư về nhựa tại ClientEarth, cho biết, nhựa sử dụng một lần không mang tính tuần hoàn cũng như không bền vững và việc tái chế không bao giờ có thể bắt kịp với khối lượng nhựa khổng lồ được sản xuất trên toàn cầu.  Ví dụ như các chai dầu gội Head and Vais của P&G được quảng cáo là được làm từ “nhựa bãi biển”, nhưng chai được nhuộm màu xanh lam, nghĩa là nó không thể tái chế được nữa. Hay như #Unilever đã thay thế các chai nước rửa PET có thể tái chế bằng túi như một phần trong nỗ lực khuyến khích đổ đầy. Nhưng báo cáo cho biết các túi này không thể tái chế được và chỉ chứa hai lần nạp lại. Coca-cola - tập đoàn nước giải khát lớn nhất thế giới với hơn 200 sản phẩm lưu hành trên thị trường và bán ra khoảng 1,6 tỷ chai mỗi ngày trên toàn thế giới. Tương đương với lượng tiêu thụ gần như 200K chai nhựa mỗi phút và tạo ra 2,9 triệu tấn rác nhựa mỗi năm. #mêbrands #xaydungthuonghieu #brand #brandstory #branding  #brandingstrategy #thuonghieu #marketing #marketingontiktok  #chienluocmarketing #LearnOnTikTok #hocmarketing #thitruong #KSCNet #scandal #casestudy

When finding live sand dollars, dont keep them out of the water very long since they are sensitive.  The yellow substance being left on the skin is echinochrome, which means they are stressed.  We found many more a few yards off shoreline since they like to live in crowded groups.  It is illegal to keep live sand dollars like this so i am sharing this education to help others.  When you find a sand dollar that is dark in color, look for these moving cilia, or hair like spines, which indicate its still alive.  Release gently deeper in the water and watch how quick it is to bury itself in the sand. What sets Blue Magic Tire Dressing apart is its solvent-based formula, featuring potent cleaning and degreasing agents. These solvents work diligently to break down stubborn contaminants and grime, leaving your tires and trim immaculately clean and perfectly prepared for the dressing. The durability of solvent-based tire dressings is another notable feature. They withstand the challenges of frequent washes and rain, ensuring your tires maintain their pristine appearance. Blue Magic Tire Dressing is typically available in spray or liquid form, making the application process quick and effortless. To achieve the best results, follow these general steps when using Blue Magic and other solvent-based tire dressings: Start by cleaning the tire thoroughly with soap and water to remove surface-level dirt. Shake the bottle, then apply the dressing by spraying it directly onto the tire and an applicator, such as a sponge, pad, or brush. Ensure even application, allowing the dressing to penetrate the wheel for a few minutes to tackle stubborn grime. Use a clean microfiber towel to remove any excess product, minimizing the risk of sling. The hardest calamities are the ones that strike without warning. Sudden. Unexpected. No time to prepare, no chance to say goodbye. Burying a loved one is never easy — but burying your child, your nine-year-old son, the love of your life… there are no words for that pain. Only Allah can give strength in a moment like that. Today, we washed and buried a little boy. And wallahi, it was one of the hardest washes I’ve ever done. The body was small, but the grief was heavy. I can’t help but go home and reflect — every day, every burial, I ask myself… who is next? “Indeed we belong to Allah, and indeed to Him we will return.” — [Surah Al-Baqarah, 2:156] May Allah grant his parents patience and firmness in their hearts. And may He grant this little boy a grave of paradise — full of light, mercy, and peace — until they reunite in Jannah.

**Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl**

Get ready for a flavor explosion with this incredible Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl! Perfect for a cozy night in or impressing your guests, this dish is a vibrant and mouthwatering experience you won't forget.

**Ingredients:**

- 1 1/2 lbs chicken breast
- 3 cups flour
- Peanut oil (for frying)
- 1/2 cup corn starch
- 1 red bell pepper, diced
- 1 can of chickpeas, rinsed and drained
- 1 can of black beans, rinsed and drained
- 1 can of red kidney beans, rinsed and drained
- 1 red onion, finely diced
- 1 cucumber, diced (peeling is optional)
- 1 cup bulgur, cooked to perfection
- 1 cup couscous, cooked and fluffy
- Green onion for a fresh garnish
- Lime wedges for that zesty kick

**Hot Honey Sweet Chili Sauce:**

- 1 Tbsp minced garlic
- 2 Tbsp minced yellow onion
- 1/2 stick of unsalted butter
- 3 1/2 Tbsp raw honey
- 1/4 cup sweet chili sauce
- 3 Tbsp Frank’s Hot Sauce
- 1 Tbsp sriracha
- 1 tsp onion powder
- 1/2 tsp garlic powder
- 2 Tbsp rice wine vinegar
- Salt and pepper to taste

**Let’s Get Cooking!**

Kick things off by infusing your chicken breast with an array of vibrant flavors! Season it generously with chili powder, garlic powder, onion powder, paprika, cracked pepper, and a sprinkle of sea salt. A splash of avocado oil and a dollop of Greek yogurt will ensure your chicken stays juicy and delicious as it marinates in this flavor bomb!

Next, create a fabulous egg wash and mix your seasoned flour to coat that chicken. The flour should be a reflection of all those delectable spices we just added!

Heat that peanut oil to a sizzling 175 degrees Fahrenheit and watch the magic happen as you dredge your chicken in the egg wash, then in your seasoned flour before frying until it’s golden brown and perfectly crispy.

While the chicken is frying to perfection, let’s prep the colorful medley of beans and veggies! Open those cans, give them a rinse, and let them drain, then chop up that red bell pepper, red onion, cucumber, and get those vibrant green onions ready for garnish.

Now for the pièce de résistance: take those juicy, crispy chicken pieces and toss them in your homemade hot honey sauce! 

Assemble your bowl with layers of flavor, showcasing each ingredient beautifully. Finally, drizzle that mouthwatering hot honey sauce all over your creation, topping it off with a sprinkle of green onion and fresh lime wedges to elevate the taste and appeal.

Your sensational Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl is ready to devour! Enjoy every bite!                                                 #food #fyppppppppppppppppppppppp

Is Acure sustainable or is it greenwashing?

Welcome to “sustainable or greenwashing month” where everyday leading up to Earth Month I’m sharing if brands and products are actually what they say they are. 

Acure was founded ***to make clean beauty products accessible.***

Their products are vegan and leaping bunny cruelty-free as well as Paraben free, Sulfate free & Phthalate free. They also note they are free from mineral oil, petrolatum and formaldehyde (don’t usually see those claims in the beuaty industry but I’ll take it??).

Packaging is made from recycled materials, and is recyclable or compostable after use. I like how Acure partners with TerraCycle to recycle their packaging. They also support a couple of nonprofts like Turning Green and Unite for Her to give back

They mention they’re working towards a Climate Neutral Certification, but they don’t say much on how or when they expect to actually achieve it. And they also say their products are manufactured in the **United States in ethical factories, but again no information on what exactly that means or how they audit their factories.**

I want to note that Acure is a family owned company, so I want to give them some grace, but overall - Acure wouldn’t be my top choice for sustainable skincare, but they also aren’t the worst option out there. Some of their claims don’t have enough information behind them which leads me to say it’s a liiiiittle bit greenwash-y. 

But what do you think? This month we’re doing an ENTIRE month of Sustainable or Greenwashing videos, so if there is a brand you want to see, stick around because it’s probably coming next! 

#sustainableorgreenwashing #acure

Is Stanley sustainable or is it greenwashing? 

Welcome to Sustainable or Greenwashing month, where all month I’m sharing if brands and products are actually what they say they are. 

Stanley has become HUGE in the last couple of years with different color way releases and collaborations (like Starbucks, Target, and more), so going into this research, you can say I’m pleasantly surprised! The biggest problem with Stanley is that people buy multiple of their signature cups which is overconsumption and defeats the purpose of reusable water bottles.

But they do check my boxes of sustainable values and initiatives - plus their bottles are meant to last a lifetime. So as long as you are not over consuming them, I think Stanley is sustainable. But what do you think?

Is Blueland sustainable or is it greenwashing?

Welcome to the series where I see if brands and products are actually what they say they are. 

The amount of comments I get to research Blueland is astronomical - so here it is! 

Blueland offers refillable cleaning products to promote eliminating single use plastics. They’re a certified B-Corp, gluten free, Paraben free, vegan, and leaping bunny cruelty free plus every ingredient is on the EPA Safer Chemical Ingredients list. The company is also Carbon Neutral Certified, Cradle to Cradle Certified, USDA BioPreferred, and they’re packaging is plastic free and compostable. Lastly, the dish soap, dishwasher & laundry tabs are all EWG verified. 

I will say the spray bottles ARE made of plastic though, which surprised me but isn’t a true dealbreaker since you can always use your own.

Overall, Blueland is a great example of a brand who is transparent with their initiatives and also also markets their products in an ethical way. SO I’d say Blueland is sustainable - but what do you think?

“reef safe” is simply a label that companies can put on their sunscreen to make it appear to be marine life friendly, but it’s not actually a true certification 

scientists are continuing to research sunscreen toxicity and are learning that some of the ingredients that have been deemed reef safe are not actually as good as we once thought

For now though, the best we know to use are Zinc Oxide (non-nano) and Titanium Dioxide like are used in @Babo Botanicals! So check your ingredients list before just buying “reef safe” sunscreens!

Is Burt’s Bees sustainable or is it greenwashing?

Welcome to the series where I see if brands and products are actually what they say they are. We have a whole month of sustainable or greenwashing videos leading up to Earth month, so let’s hop into it. 

Starting off, Burts Bees was founded as a back-to-the-basics product that connects to nature. It’s leaping Bunny cruelty free, but not vegan (since they use Beeswax). They’re Carbon Neutral Certified, and source their beeswax from communities in Eastern Africa who wild-craft the beeswax. All palm oil used is ethically sourced (RSPO Certified).

The tubes are made with a combo of PCR plastic & bio plastic AND they now offer chapstick in cardboard which I LOVE (!!!) and also recently released home compostable wipes.

In 2021 they transitioned to 100% renewable electricity in their manufacturing facilities & they seem to be transparent about channeling any operational waste into compost and recycling in their facilities.

Burts Bees is owned by Clorox, but they partner with rePurpose Global to help clear plastic from oceans, and invest in national parks.

SO WITH THAT, I’d say Burt’s Bees is pretty sustainable - but what do you think?

If you have a FRONT-loading washing machine—you NEED to know THIS ⚠️ You might be unintentionally poisoning yourself due to the TOXIC mold it creates. ❌ Mold—and the mycotoxins it produces—is among the most dangerous natural substances that can exist in your home!  Front-loading washing machines are often breeding grounds for black toxic mold. When you wash your clothes in them, mold and mycotoxins can embed in the fabric and you’ll be breathing them in and absorbing them through your skin all the time.  ‍ Non-Toxic Dad recommendation: If you have a front-loading washing machine, get rid of it as soon as you can!  Replace it with a top-loading washing machine.  If replacing it isn’t an option right now, search online for nontoxic ways to remove the mold. Use natural cleansers like baking soda—not bleach! It might not be cheap in the short run, but it could save your health in the long run. ❤️ #NonToxicLiving #NonToxic #Toxic #HealthyLiving #Health #CleanHome

Free People markets itself as a boho, conscious fashion brand. In reality, it’s part of URBN Inc., a billion-dollar corporation that also owns Urban Outfitters and Anthropologie and the rental app Nuuly  Some pieces are labeled “responsible” with little backing. Most materials are conventional cotton, synthetics and a bit of rayon. The leadership is largely held within one family, and the company has faced multiple labor and ethics concerns, including recent supplier layoffs in Mauritius. Is 9 Elements sustainable or is it greenwashing? Welcome to “sustainable or greenwashing month” where everyday leading up to Earth Month I’m sharing if brands and products are actually what they say they are. ️‍♀️ 9 Elements is a household cleaner and detergent brand found at most grocery stores, and it gets its name from the ingredients list being 9 ingredients or less - not bad! One thing I noticed right off that bat is that the main marketed ingredient is vinegar, and their marketing really plays on the DIY vinegar solutions, but I find that a little misleading since vinegar isn’t the main* cleaning ingredient in any these products. *Vinegar is towards the bottom of their ingredient list. Their products are made with no synthetic fragrances or Artificial preservatives & I do like that the all of their products are at least 50% USDA Biobased Certified **&** meets the EPA Safer Choice standard. Other than that, the brand has ZERO sustainable initiatives, no information regarding ingredient sourcing or manufacturing practices, and is not cruelty free. They don’t seem to be active in any community efforts, they’re packaged with a LOT of plastic, and they’re owned by P&G. So while I would say they have clean ingredients, I wouldn’t call this brand sustainable. So it feels greenwash-y to me - but what do you think? This month we’re doing an ENTIRE month of Sustainable or Greenwashing videos, so if there is a brand you want to see, stick around because it’s probably coming!  #sustainableorgreenwashing #9elements

Remember when people were fighting over Stanley cups last year in a Lewis Rd Creamery way? (Also, still want to know if that was faked - genius.) Now those reusable cups are piling up in second hand stores. Colour me shocked ‍♀️.  You have to give it to Stanley though - that was a phenomenal branding moment and they milked it. But now they've leaned too far into it and for a brand that calls itself sustainable, it's not really being sustainable. This is what so many brands do. They manufacture hype and push overconsumption while calling on the consumer to recycle .  Fine. You kind of expect that from them. But it really annoys me when you see self-proclaimed ‘sustainable’ brands that do the same with constant merch drops and limited editions that are just different colours. It doesn't matter if your product is reusable, it doesn't make you sustainable. In fact, if people are going to treat Stanley's like this, you'd be better off buying single-use  You have to use your stainless steel Stanley at least 100-120 times for it to have less impact than a single-use cup.  Something to ponder. Thanks to @Alyssa Barber for the video at the start! #sustainability #greenwashing #stanleycup #stanley #science

Thanksgiving Recipes Episode 2: creamy scalloped potatoes with carmelized onions Hope you guys enjoy this one!! Recipe down below :) Ingredients: • 1 large yellow onion • 2.5lbs of yukon gold potatoes • 2 tbsp butter (salted) • 6 cloves garlic, minced (use more or less to your preference) • 5-6 peppercorns (or 1tsp pepper) • 2tbsp flour • 2 cups heavy cream • 1 heavy pinch salt & white pepper (you can leave the white pepper out) • 1 sprig each rosemary & thyme (also optional)  • 8oz gruyere cheese • 8oz parmesan cheese • 6oz colby jack cheese  • chives for garnish (optional)  *NOTE: you do not have to carmelize the onions! But please try it if you can!! DIRECTIONS: 1. Start by slicing the onion into long, thin strips. Then, throw them in a medium heat pan with 1tbsp oil 2. Cook them on medium heat for the first 10 minutes, stirring often. After 10 minutes, turn the heat down to low and continue stirring every couple of minutes. Around the 30-40 minute mark they should be super soft and brown. Set to the side. 3. In a pot on medium heat, add in the butter, garlic, peppercorn, and flour  4. Stir the ingredients until they begin browning (3 mins) and then add in the heavy cream, salt, pepper, and herbs. Allow to simmer on very low heat for 15 mins. 5. Wash, peel, and slice your potatoes thin 6. In a baking dish (I used a 60oz oval dish) grease it with some butter, then start layering. 7. Make a layer of potato, gruyere & parmesan, and the carmelized onion 8. Repeat step 7, then add on half of the creamy sauce (pass it through a strainer first!!) 9. For the third layer, you’ll put potato, the sauce, gruyere, colby jack, and more gruyere 10. Put the dish into a 315 degree oven for 1.5hrs. Slow cooking is best, but to save time, you can also cook it at 350 for 50 minutes or until golden brown on top 11. Keep checking the oven after 40 minutes to ensure it does not burn. 12. Top with chives and Enjoy :) Thank you guys • #thanksgiving #thanksgivingrecipes #easyrecipe #cheese #scallopedpotatoes #potatoes #thanksgivingdinner #cooking #carmelizedonions #onion

This is a dry cleaners recommendations on how often you should be washing your stuff: 1) Gym clothes - after every use (maybe less for bottoms) 2) Bath towels - once a week 3) Comforters - every few months 4) Dresses - a few wears 5) Jeans - once a year, unless you're wearing them often when doing hands on physical work 6) Outerwear - infrequently, but before you put them away for the season 7) Sheets - once a week if you can, but washing away the body oils will prevent yellowing 8) Suits - every few months unless they start to get wrinkled or smell 9) Sweaters - every few months but before you put them away for the season! This will help prevent moth damage 10) Swimwear - rinse after every use and wash after a few uses 11) Tee shirts - every few uses but youll figure it out 12) Undergarments - after every wear #howoftenshouldiwashmystuff #laundry #laundrytips #laundryhacks #clean #cleaning #cleanclothes #cleansheets #howtodoalundry #cleaningtips #cleandenim #towelcleaning

**Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl**

Get ready for a flavor explosion with this incredible Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl! Perfect for a cozy night in or impressing your guests, this dish is a vibrant and mouthwatering experience you won't forget.

**Ingredients:**

- 1 1/2 lbs chicken breast
- 3 cups flour
- Peanut oil (for frying)
- 1/2 cup corn starch
- 1 red bell pepper, diced
- 1 can of chickpeas, rinsed and drained
- 1 can of black beans, rinsed and drained
- 1 can of red kidney beans, rinsed and drained
- 1 red onion, finely diced
- 1 cucumber, diced (peeling is optional)
- 1 cup bulgur, cooked to perfection
- 1 cup couscous, cooked and fluffy
- Green onion for a fresh garnish
- Lime wedges for that zesty kick

**Hot Honey Sweet Chili Sauce:**

- 1 Tbsp minced garlic
- 2 Tbsp minced yellow onion
- 1/2 stick of unsalted butter
- 3 1/2 Tbsp raw honey
- 1/4 cup sweet chili sauce
- 3 Tbsp Frank’s Hot Sauce
- 1 Tbsp sriracha
- 1 tsp onion powder
- 1/2 tsp garlic powder
- 2 Tbsp rice wine vinegar
- Salt and pepper to taste

**Let’s Get Cooking!**

Kick things off by infusing your chicken breast with an array of vibrant flavors! Season it generously with chili powder, garlic powder, onion powder, paprika, cracked pepper, and a sprinkle of sea salt. A splash of avocado oil and a dollop of Greek yogurt will ensure your chicken stays juicy and delicious as it marinates in this flavor bomb!

Next, create a fabulous egg wash and mix your seasoned flour to coat that chicken. The flour should be a reflection of all those delectable spices we just added!

Heat that peanut oil to a sizzling 175 degrees Fahrenheit and watch the magic happen as you dredge your chicken in the egg wash, then in your seasoned flour before frying until it’s golden brown and perfectly crispy.

While the chicken is frying to perfection, let’s prep the colorful medley of beans and veggies! Open those cans, give them a rinse, and let them drain, then chop up that red bell pepper, red onion, cucumber, and get those vibrant green onions ready for garnish.

Now for the pièce de résistance: take those juicy, crispy chicken pieces and toss them in your homemade hot honey sauce! 

Assemble your bowl with layers of flavor, showcasing each ingredient beautifully. Finally, drizzle that mouthwatering hot honey sauce all over your creation, topping it off with a sprinkle of green onion and fresh lime wedges to elevate the taste and appeal.

Your sensational Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl is ready to devour! Enjoy every bite!                                                 #food #fyppppppppppppppppppppppp

Thanksgiving Recipes Episode 2: creamy scalloped potatoes with carmelized onions Hope you guys enjoy this one!! Recipe down below :) Ingredients: • 1 large yellow onion • 2.5lbs of yukon gold potatoes • 2 tbsp butter (salted) • 6 cloves garlic, minced (use more or less to your preference) • 5-6 peppercorns (or 1tsp pepper) • 2tbsp flour • 2 cups heavy cream • 1 heavy pinch salt & white pepper (you can leave the white pepper out) • 1 sprig each rosemary & thyme (also optional)  • 8oz gruyere cheese • 8oz parmesan cheese • 6oz colby jack cheese  • chives for garnish (optional)  *NOTE: you do not have to carmelize the onions! But please try it if you can!! DIRECTIONS: 1. Start by slicing the onion into long, thin strips. Then, throw them in a medium heat pan with 1tbsp oil 2. Cook them on medium heat for the first 10 minutes, stirring often. After 10 minutes, turn the heat down to low and continue stirring every couple of minutes. Around the 30-40 minute mark they should be super soft and brown. Set to the side. 3. In a pot on medium heat, add in the butter, garlic, peppercorn, and flour  4. Stir the ingredients until they begin browning (3 mins) and then add in the heavy cream, salt, pepper, and herbs. Allow to simmer on very low heat for 15 mins. 5. Wash, peel, and slice your potatoes thin 6. In a baking dish (I used a 60oz oval dish) grease it with some butter, then start layering. 7. Make a layer of potato, gruyere & parmesan, and the carmelized onion 8. Repeat step 7, then add on half of the creamy sauce (pass it through a strainer first!!) 9. For the third layer, you’ll put potato, the sauce, gruyere, colby jack, and more gruyere 10. Put the dish into a 315 degree oven for 1.5hrs. Slow cooking is best, but to save time, you can also cook it at 350 for 50 minutes or until golden brown on top 11. Keep checking the oven after 40 minutes to ensure it does not burn. 12. Top with chives and Enjoy :) Thank you guys • #thanksgiving #thanksgivingrecipes #easyrecipe #cheese #scallopedpotatoes #potatoes #thanksgivingdinner #cooking #carmelizedonions #onion

How does Super Blue rinse work?  It’s a genius concept called colour theory. Imagine if you joined the two ends of the rainbow together to form a wheel. The colours that sit opposite each other can effectively cancel each other out and neutralise them. This explains why this blue pigment will neutralise the yellow and discoloured areas on greys and light-coloured horses and ponies, as well as enhancing the natural hair colour.  #bluerinse #superblue #deeppurple #whitehorses #greyhorse #greys #shampoo #horsegroominghack #horsegroom #horsehack #horses #equestrian #equinelife #horsegirl

**Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl**

Get ready for a flavor explosion with this incredible Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl! Perfect for a cozy night in or impressing your guests, this dish is a vibrant and mouthwatering experience you won't forget.

**Ingredients:**

- 1 1/2 lbs chicken breast
- 3 cups flour
- Peanut oil (for frying)
- 1/2 cup corn starch
- 1 red bell pepper, diced
- 1 can of chickpeas, rinsed and drained
- 1 can of black beans, rinsed and drained
- 1 can of red kidney beans, rinsed and drained
- 1 red onion, finely diced
- 1 cucumber, diced (peeling is optional)
- 1 cup bulgur, cooked to perfection
- 1 cup couscous, cooked and fluffy
- Green onion for a fresh garnish
- Lime wedges for that zesty kick

**Hot Honey Sweet Chili Sauce:**

- 1 Tbsp minced garlic
- 2 Tbsp minced yellow onion
- 1/2 stick of unsalted butter
- 3 1/2 Tbsp raw honey
- 1/4 cup sweet chili sauce
- 3 Tbsp Frank’s Hot Sauce
- 1 Tbsp sriracha
- 1 tsp onion powder
- 1/2 tsp garlic powder
- 2 Tbsp rice wine vinegar
- Salt and pepper to taste

**Let’s Get Cooking!**

Kick things off by infusing your chicken breast with an array of vibrant flavors! Season it generously with chili powder, garlic powder, onion powder, paprika, cracked pepper, and a sprinkle of sea salt. A splash of avocado oil and a dollop of Greek yogurt will ensure your chicken stays juicy and delicious as it marinates in this flavor bomb!

Next, create a fabulous egg wash and mix your seasoned flour to coat that chicken. The flour should be a reflection of all those delectable spices we just added!

Heat that peanut oil to a sizzling 175 degrees Fahrenheit and watch the magic happen as you dredge your chicken in the egg wash, then in your seasoned flour before frying until it’s golden brown and perfectly crispy.

While the chicken is frying to perfection, let’s prep the colorful medley of beans and veggies! Open those cans, give them a rinse, and let them drain, then chop up that red bell pepper, red onion, cucumber, and get those vibrant green onions ready for garnish.

How To Setup Your Oral Hygiene Routine! 
 
1️⃣ Brushing first thing in the morning and before bed is key. Since you produce less saliva overnight, bad bacteria can grow overnight. You want to clear that out before you eat or drink anything.

2️⃣ Tongue scraping first thing in the AM is the best, for the same reason as brushing. You want to clear that bad bacteria off the tongue from the previous night.
 
3️⃣ Studies show us that flossing before brushing is prefered if you have the choice. You end up loosening plaque prior to brushing.
 
4️⃣ If you use a waterpik do it before you brush for the same reason and sometimes you can choose to use it instead of floss.
 
5️⃣ Some people truly love oil pulling and in my opinion it would work best to do it after tongue scraping, but before you floss or brush, so you can thoroughly rinse.
 
6️⃣ I’m not a huge mouthwash fan, but if you do use it I would recommend using it prior to brushing also, because you want the toothpaste to sit on your teeth after you brush. This would be true for most toothpaste options. If you use mouthwash you end up washing this away.

PHO INSPIRED CHICKEN BROTH & RICE  Broth  - 6 star anise  - 5 cardamon pods  - - - 1 tsp coriander seeds  - 1 tsp cloves  - 1 Cinnamon quill  - 1 white onion, roughly chopped  - 1 spring onion, roughly chopped  - 3 garlic cloves, roughly chopped  - 5 pieces of slices ginger  -  3 cups chicken broth  - 1 tbsp fish sauce  - 1 tsp soy sauce  - 1 bunch of coriander roots  - 1 tbsp palm sugar or brown sugar  Rice  - 1 tsp sesame oil  - 2 garlic cloves, finely chopped  - 2cm piece of ginger, grated  - 2 tbsp coriander, finely chopped  - 2 tbsp mint, finely chopped  - 1/2 cup jasmine rice, washed  - 1 slice of lemon  - 1 cup of water  Chicken  - 1 chicken breast, cut in half  - 1/4 cup of hoisin  - 1 tsp miso paste  - 1 tbsp honey  - 1 tbsp Fish Sauce  - 1 tsp gochujang  - Good scrunch of pepper  Other ingredients  - 2 spring onions  - Bok choy  - Black sesame seeds, for garnish  - Fried shallots, for garnish  - Coriander, for garnish  Method  • Start with the broth. Dry fry the onion, spring onion, ginger & garlic until charred, then add the chicken broth, aromatics, fish sauce, soy sauce & the coriander roots. Then let that simmer with the lid on whilst you make the rice. • For the rice, sauté the garlic, ginger, coriander & mint in the sesame oil, before adding in the rice, lemon & water. Cook with the lid on until fluffy.  • For the chicken, mix together the hoisin, miso, honey, fish sauce, gochujang & pepper. Toss the chicken until coated.  • Fry in a pan the chicken on both sides until golden & sauce is sticky.  • In the same pan, cook the spring onion & wok chop with a splash of water.  • Finish the broth off with the sugar, stir until dissolved, then pass through a sieve.  •  Garnish & enjoy  #chicken #rice #broth #gochujang #pho #chickenandrice #comfortfood #dinner #dinnerisready #easydinner #wintermeal #soup #30minutemeals #chickenriceandbroth #ricesoup #vietnamesefood #viralfood #charredchicken #juicychicken

Mac n Cheese w/ Sticky Ribs! ️ Mac n Cheese Ingredients:  Bechamel:  2tbsp Butter  1tsp Onion Powder  1tsp Garlic Powder  1tsp Paprika  Pinch of Salt  Pinch of Pepper  1tsp Mixed Herbs  3-4tbsp Flour  500ml Milk (1 Pint)  Handful of Cheddar Handful of Red Leicester  Handful of Fresh Mozzarella Ball (grated)  1tbsp Cream Cheese / Boursin  150ml Double Cream  300g Macaroni Pasta (al dente) 1tbsp Butter  Extra Grated Cheeses  Beef or Lamb Ribs (15): Marinade:  BBQ seasoning (any) 1.5tbsp 1tsp Cumin  1tsp Ground Coriander  1tsp Chilli Powder  1tsp Garlic Powder 1tsp Onion Powder 1tsp Paprika 1tsp Salt.  1tsp Pepper  0.5tsp Mixed Herbs (Oregano, Thyme, Parsley, Rosemary)  Pinch of Garam Masala  1tbsp Brown Sugar / Honey  1tbsp Ginger (minced) 5 Garlic Cloves (minced) 3tbsp BBQ Sauce  2tbsp Brown Sugar  1tbsp Chilli Flakes  1tsp Garlic Powder  1tsp Onion Powder  1tbsp Paprika 1tsp Salt 1tsp Pepper 1tbsp Mustard Oil Recipe:  - Wash & pat dry your ribs, cover in powdered seasonings, wrap in foil and bake at 170C for 60mins (low and slow!) - Mix together the bbq sauce seasonings  - Keep basting the ribs in its melted fats and coat in the bbq sauce, multiple time throughout the hour, keep it covered!  - After an hour, remove the foil and reduce for 15mins until thick and sticky, keep brushing the juices to prevent burning - Add macaroni to boiling water (al dente)  - For the béchamel, melt butter in a pan, add your seasonings and cook for a couple mins (to max the flavour)  - Add the flour by spoon, and whisk in until thick dough formed  - Cook the dough for a couple mins, gradually add the milk until smooth, keep adding until thick sauce is formed  - Add the cream & cream cheese - Add grated cheeses until melted  - Drain the pasta, add to the dish, mix in butter and extra grated cheeses  - Add cheese sauce and mix in  - Add extra layer of sauce on top, grated cheeses, parsley & pepper  - Bake at 180C for 25mins! This is your sign to make applesauce instead of buying it this year  (Hint: Go on an apple picking date!) #homemadeisbetter #applesauce #canning #preserving #applepicking #dateideas   Homemade Applesauce (Water Bath Canning Safe)  Ingredients: 6 pounds of apples (about 12–15 medium apples; mix of sweet and tart is best) ½ to 1 cup water or apple cider Optional: 1–2 tablespoons lemon juice (helps preserve color) ¼ to ½ cup sugar (or to taste — you can skip this) ½–1 teaspoon cinnamon (or other warm spices, optional)  Instructions: 1. Prep the Apples Wash, peel, core, and chop the apples into chunks. To prevent browning while prepping, toss chopped apples with lemon juice or keep them in a bowl of water with lemon juice added. 2. Cook the Apples In a large pot, combine apples with water (or cider). Cover and simmer over medium-low heat until apples are soft (15–25 minutes), stirring occasionally. Add more water if needed to prevent sticking. 3. Puree or Mash For smooth applesauce: Use an immersion blender, food processor, or food mill. For chunky applesauce: Mash with a potato masher. Taste and add sugar/spices if desired. Simmer a few more minutes to dissolve. 4. Prepare for Canning Sterilize jars (usually pints or quarts) in boiling water or a dishwasher on the sanitize cycle. Warm your lids and bands in hot (not boiling) water. 5. Fill the Jars Ladle hot applesauce into hot, sterilized jars, leaving ½-inch headspace. Remove air bubbles, wipe the rims clean with a damp cloth, and apply lids and bands (finger-tight). 6. Water Bath Can Place jars in a boiling water canner. Ensure they’re fully submerged with at least 1 inch of water above the lids. Process jars: Pints or quarts: 20 minutes (adjust for altitude—see below). Start timing once water returns to a boil. 7. Cool & Store Carefully remove jars and let them cool, undisturbed, for 12–24 hours. Check seals (lid should not flex). Label and store in a cool, dark place. Shelf life: Up to 18 months  when properly sealed and stored.

This laundry setting will save you hundreds every year and nobody talks about it!    Cold water washing has real benefits, but I want to give you the accurate facts so you can make smart decisions about your laundry: ✨    Keeps colors from fading and bleeding (heat opens fibers, releasing dyes)    Reduces your washing machine's energy use by up to 90%    Prevents heat-induced shrinkage and fabric damage    Significantly reduces your environmental impact   ⚡ Modern detergents contain enzymes that work effectively in cold water   Here's when cold water works best: everyday laundry, lightly soiled items, synthetic fabrics, and delicate colors!    But let's be honest.   Hot water still wins for heavily soiled items, grease stains, protein stains like blood or sweat, and when you need true sanitization.   That's just science!    The smart approach? Use cold water as your default and switch to warm or hot only when you actually need that extra cleaning power.   Your clothes and wallet will thank you!    Comment "SWAP" for my free Simple Swaps guide  #cleaningtipsbytrish #trishstips #coldwater #laundry #washingclothes #howtodolaundry #savemoney #laundryhacks #laundryhelp #washingmachine #energybill #laundrytips #moneysaving #cleancloths #housework #laundryroom

To run your dishwasher without traditional dishwashing detergent, you can use an alternative method. Load your dirty dishes as usual, but instead of detergent, add 3-5 drops of regular dish soap in the detergent compartment. Then, some baking soda in the main wash section and pour about 5 bottle caps of vinegar into the rinse aid compartment. Start the dishwasher as you normally would, and let this combination of ingredients work its magic. The dish soap helps remove grease, the baking soda scrubs away stains, and the vinegar assists in rinsing and adding shine. After the cycle is complete, your dishes should be clean and ready to use, but remember.  #disheshack #diswasher #savemoneytips #budgeting #fyp

How to overdye jeans What happens when you put blue jeans in yellow dye? Give your jeans a refresh for Spring with this easy upcycle diy project! 1️⃣ Pre-wash jeans, and keep fabric damp. 2️⃣ Fill a large pot with hot water, 1 cup of salt, and 1 teaspoon of dish soap. There must be enough water to fully submerge the jeans and stir them easily. 3️⃣ Put on rubber gloves, and shake dye bottle well. Add half a bottle of Rit All Purpose Dye in Lemon Yellow to pot. 4️⃣ Place pot on stovetop, and set to medium heat. 5️⃣ Add jeans to dye bath. Stir jeans constantly for 30 minutes and make sure all areas of the fabric get submerged evenly. Use tongs to help separate any folds in the fabric. 6️⃣ To lock in your color and reduce bleeding, use RIT ColorStay Dye fixative. Fill a sink or bucket with 3 gallons of hot water and add half a bottle of the Dye Fixative. Move jeans immediately from the dye bath to the prepared Dye Fixative bath. Stir jeans for 20 minutes. 7️⃣ Rinse jeans in sink with cool water until water runs clear. 8️⃣ Wash jeans by hand or washing machine (by themselves) with mild detergent and warm water.  #ritdye #upcycle #thriftflip #fabricdyeing #reworkedclothing

Time for a deep dive into: algae-based bioplastics! 

Researchers at the University of California San Diego first invented a bio-based polyurethane plastic out of algae almost a decade ago, and after years of experimentation they can now confidently say it biodegrades without producing microplastics.

This breakthrough proves that replacing petroleum-based plastics with plant-based ones is absolutely possible, but it’s going to take a lot of infrastructure, incentives, and investment to scale it up.

Sources: Nature, University of California San Diego, NBC

How to overdye jeans What happens when you put blue jeans in yellow dye? Give your jeans a refresh for Spring with this easy upcycle diy project! 1️⃣ Pre-wash jeans, and keep fabric damp. 2️⃣ Fill a large pot with hot water, 1 cup of salt, and 1 teaspoon of dish soap. There must be enough water to fully submerge the jeans and stir them easily. 3️⃣ Put on rubber gloves, and shake dye bottle well. Add half a bottle of Rit All Purpose Dye in Lemon Yellow to pot. 4️⃣ Place pot on stovetop, and set to medium heat. 5️⃣ Add jeans to dye bath. Stir jeans constantly for 30 minutes and make sure all areas of the fabric get submerged evenly. Use tongs to help separate any folds in the fabric. 6️⃣ To lock in your color and reduce bleeding, use RIT ColorStay Dye fixative. Fill a sink or bucket with 3 gallons of hot water and add half a bottle of the Dye Fixative. Move jeans immediately from the dye bath to the prepared Dye Fixative bath. Stir jeans for 20 minutes. 7️⃣ Rinse jeans in sink with cool water until water runs clear. 8️⃣ Wash jeans by hand or washing machine (by themselves) with mild detergent and warm water.  #ritdye #upcycle #thriftflip #fabricdyeing #reworkedclothing

How to overdye jeans What happens when you put blue jeans in yellow dye? Give your jeans a refresh for Spring with this easy upcycle diy project! 1️⃣ Pre-wash jeans, and keep fabric damp. 2️⃣ Fill a large pot with hot water, 1 cup of salt, and 1 teaspoon of dish soap. There must be enough water to fully submerge the jeans and stir them easily. 3️⃣ Put on rubber gloves, and shake dye bottle well. Add half a bottle of Rit All Purpose Dye in Lemon Yellow to pot. 4️⃣ Place pot on stovetop, and set to medium heat. 5️⃣ Add jeans to dye bath. Stir jeans constantly for 30 minutes and make sure all areas of the fabric get submerged evenly. Use tongs to help separate any folds in the fabric. 6️⃣ To lock in your color and reduce bleeding, use RIT ColorStay Dye fixative. Fill a sink or bucket with 3 gallons of hot water and add half a bottle of the Dye Fixative. Move jeans immediately from the dye bath to the prepared Dye Fixative bath. Stir jeans for 20 minutes. 7️⃣ Rinse jeans in sink with cool water until water runs clear. 8️⃣ Wash jeans by hand or washing machine (by themselves) with mild detergent and warm water.  #ritdye #upcycle #thriftflip #fabricdyeing #reworkedclothing

Just in time for Mother’s Day, this overnight berry french toast casserole is the perfect make-ahead brunch!  #overnight #berry #frenchtoast #casserole #mothersday #brunch #breakfast #ideas #recipe #carnationmilk #evaporatedmilk #recipes #carnationnation  Overnight Berry French Toast Casserole Serves 8-10 Ingredients 1 14-16oz loaf of Brioche or Challah bread, cubed into 1-inch pieces 8 eggs 2 ½ cups of Carnation Evaporated Milk 1 Tablespoon vanilla extract ½ teaspoon cinnamon 2 cups of washed and dried berries like strawberries (sliced), blueberries, and raspberries 1 Tablespoon softened butter Streusel topping ½ cup of cold unsalted butter, cubed ½ cup brown sugar ½ cup all-purpose flour ½ teaspoon cinnamon ¼ teaspoon salt How to make berry overnight French toast casserole 1. Butter a 9x13 baking dish with the softened butter. Pour the cubed brioche bread into the pan. Top the bread with the mixed berries and set aside. 2. To a large bowl, add the eggs, Carnation Evaporated Milk, vanilla, brown sugar, and cinnamon. Whisk until everything is combined. 3. Carefully pour the egg mixture over the top of the bread and berries. Gently press the bread into the liquid. Cover and refrigerate for at least 4 hours, preferably overnight. 4. The next day, remove the casserole from the fridge and preheat the oven to 350 degrees. 5. Prepare the streusel topping by combining the brown sugar, cinnamon, flour, and salt until combined. Cut in the cold butter with a pastry cutter or 2 forks. Sprinkle the streusel over the top of the French toast casserole. Place in the oven and bake for 45-55 minutes depending on how soft you like it. We baked ours for 45 minutes for a softer consistency. 6. Remove from the oven and allow it to cool in the pan for 5 minutes. Serve warm with a dusting of powdered sugar and maple syrup for the ultimate Mother’s Day brunch!

Baghali Polo ba Mahicheh  Persian dill rice with fava beans served with braised lamb shanks. A delicacy loved by everyone at Persian parties.  Ingredients (serves 3-4) - 3 lbs lamb shanks - 2 large onions - 6-8 cloves of garlic - 1 tablespoon salt - 1/2 teaspoon turmeric  - 1/2 teaspoon black pepper  - 3 tablespoons liquid saffron  - 1 cinnamon stick Dill Rice Ingredients: - 2 cups rice - 1 tablespoon salt - 4 tablespoons dill weed - 1 teaspoon cinnamon powder  - 4 tablespoons butter or ghee - 400 grams fava beans  Instructions: - Wash and pat dry the lamb shanks with a paper towel. In a large frying pan, heat up some olive oil, add the lamb shanks, add salt, turmeric and black pepper. Saute both sides on high heat. Then set them aside.  - Use the same frying pan and leftover olive oil to saute two thinly sliced large onions. Fry till onions are golden brown tgen add garlic cloves and lamb shanks on top of the onions. Add a cinnamon stick to the pan. Pour some liquid saffron over the lamb shanks. Then add enough boiling water to fill up half of the pan. Cover and cook on low for 1 1/2 hours. Then rotate the lamb shanks and adjust the salt. Cover and cook on low for another 1 1/2 hours.  - In a small pot, bring some water to boil. Then add the fava beans and cook till they are tender. Some fava beans take a while to cook while some take a few minutes to cook, so keep an eye on them when they are cooking or they may turn out mushy. Then drain the beans and run cold water over them to stop cooking. Baghali Polo with potato tahdig: - Wash and soak rice in lukewarm water with a tablespoon of salt for one hour. To make the rice, drain the water used for soaking, then add the rice to a pot of boiling water. Cook on high for 6-8 minutes until rice is 80% cooked. Then add the fava beans to the rice. Stir well then drain them. Add some olive oil and 1 tablespoon liquid saffron to the pot. Cover the bottom of the pot with potato slices. Add half of the rice to the pot, sprinkle two tablespoons dried dill weed to the rice. Mix well. Add the remaining rice and another 2 tablespoons of dill weed on top. Mix well. Sprinkle some cinnamon and add 4 tablespoons of butter on top. Cover and cook on low for 45 minutes. Flip the rice on a big platter. Serve with sliw cooked braised lamb shanks and salad Shirazi. raising canes texas toast at home ✨ - this fluffy bread recipe turned out so dang GOOD! It’s impossible to just have one!!  what you’ll need:  Texas Toast Dough • 3 cups (390g) all purpose flour, spooned and leveled  • 2 tbsp (25g) sugar, divided  • 1 1/2 tsp active dry yeast  • 1 tsp salt  • 1 large egg, whisked • 3/4 cup (177 ml) warm milk (105-110F)  • 5 tbsp (71g) unsalted butter, softened  • 1-2 tsp neutral flavored oil • 1 large egg + 1 tsp water, whisked  • Sesame seeds  Honey Butter Glaze  • 2 tbsp unsalted butter, cut into cubes • 1 tbsp honey  • Pinch of salt, optional  Toasting  • 2-4 tbsp unsalted butter, plus more as needed  here’s how to make it:    Texas Toast - In a large bowl, add and whisk together the warmed milk, 1/2 tsp sugar and the yeast. Cover bowl and set aside for 8-10 min or until the yeast mixture appears foamy. Mix in the flour, remaining sugar, salt, egg, and butter until a soft dough forms. Knead the dough in the bowl or on a floured surface for 5-6 min. Drizzle some oil over the dough. Turn the dough in the bowl to coat in oil. Cover bowl with plastic wrap/kitchen towel and place in a warm area of kitchen for 60-90 min or until the dough has doubled in size. Punch down risen dough and let it sit for 5 min before cutting into (8) equal pieces. Roll out each piece of dough into a 5x4 inch rectangle and then roll into a log shape. Place logs in a greased 9x9 inch baking pan and cover with plastic wrap/kitchen towel. Set side to rise, 25-30 min. Preheat oven to 350F. In a small dish, whisk together the egg and water. Brush rolls with egg wash and sprinkle top with sesame seeds. Bake for 25-30 min or until a toothpick inserted into one of the rolls comes out clean.  Honey Butter - in a small saucepan, add the butter, honey and salt. Cook mixture while stirring until all the butter is melted. Remove from heat.  To Serve - brush honey butter over warm rolls before serving. To serve toasted, cut the rolls in half. Melt butter in a skillet over medium heat. In batches, toast the rolls on both sides until golden brown. Serve rolls as is or with raising canes sauce. Is Grove sustainable or is it greenwashing? 

Welcome to “sustainable or greenwashing month” where everyday leading up to Earth Month I’m sharing if brands and products are actually what they say they are. ️‍♀️

Grove started as an online marketplace but has since moved into offering their own products, which is what we’re going to focus on. Grove is a B Corp, Carbon Neutral Certified, Certified Plastic Neutral, EPA Safer Choice Partner, and their products are leaping bunny cruelty free, Phthalate free, Paraben free, free of synthetic fragrances, and their core cleaning products are USDA BioPreferred.

They partner with lots of organizations to back up their claims like Beyond Plastic, The Nature Conservatory, and The Arbor Day Foundation (Grove has planted planted over a million trees since 2018).

Supplier factories are audited to insure good working conditions and their aim is to be net zero by 2030. All of that plus more is easily available on their website via a recent sustainability report and plastic scorecard which includes concrete plans and information on their goals and initiatives.

Overall Grove products are definitely a better option and I love how they are available in **[@target](https://www.tiktok.com/@target)** which makes them much more accessible for those on the go since you dont have to plan ahead & order it online. It’s also a great example of the type of certifications and credentials you should be looking for when you’re shopping - but what do you think? This month we’re doing an ENTIRE month of Sustainable or Greenwashing videos, so if there is a brand you want to see, stick around because it’s probably coming!

Is Native sustainable or is it greenwashing?

Two years ago I said it was greenwashing, so let’s see if anything has changed…

Welcome to “sustainable or greenwashing month” where I see if brands and products are actually what they say they are. ️‍♀️

Native was founded as a way to to make “clean” & “nontoxic” deodorant which has since moved into other body care products. As we know, words like “clean” and “nontoxic” aren’t regulated - so let’s dive into what that means for Native.

Ingredients are Phthalates free, Paraben free, cruelty free (without a third party certification, so to me that doesn't really count), and their scents abide by the International Fragrance Regulatory Association (IFRA). *deodorants are aluminum & talc free.

All products are made in the USA, but they are owned by P&G & their formulas are not considered biodegradable.

The cool thing about Native is they offer plastic free deodorant which I love, but they promote the brand to be 1% for the planet, but in reality it’s ONLY for the plastic free deodorant (???? thats wild to me, why is it not every product??)

I’m actually going to include a screenshot of the only environmental statement on their website here and to be honest, this is just screams greenwashing:

“Plastic doesn’t make perfect, and we’re doing our part to help. Reducing our environmental impact is nuanced, difficult, and important work—and while we can’t promise to get it right every time, we can promise to be upfront and honest about our efforts. If you’ve ever read one of our ingredient labels you know transparency is sort of our thing.”

SO, for a popular brand that would have the money and resources to do better - I’m disappointed because they definitely tout their products to be “natural” and “clean” - and maybe they are better than other brands - but they just don’t cut it for me.

I’m gonna say greenwashing - but what do you think? This month we’re doing an ENTIRE month of Sustainable or Greenwashing videos, so if there is a brand you want to see, stick around because it’s probably coming.

Is Dr. Bronners sustainable or is it greenwashing?

Let’s dive into Dr. Bronners castile soap, which is basically a type of soap you can use for pretty much anything.

First, the packaging (which is plastic) is made from 100% PCR plastic, which personally I’m okay with since most times that’s a more eco friendly option. The soap itself is completely biodegradable & one of my favorite quotes they stand by is “we are responsible for ourselves, but also each other, and as we grow we must grow responsibly”. Dr Bronner’s is a certified B Corp and the ingredients are organic, Fair Trade, EWG verified, & leaping bunny cruelty free. 

They offer a lot of information and resources on their company practices on their website - which include fair wages and good working conditions as well as their push to have all of their ingredients receive a regenerative organic certification (as of 2024 they only have coconut with the RO certification).

In 2023, they rolled out their soap in plastic free packaging, so after reviewing ALL of that - Dr. Bronner’s seems pretty sustainable to me. What do you think and what do you want to see next??

Heads up that in March we’re doing an entire month of Sustainable or greenwashing videos, so if there is a brand you want to see, speak now or forever hold your peace!

How to overdye jeans What happens when you put blue jeans in yellow dye? Give your jeans a refresh for Spring with this easy upcycle diy project! 1️⃣ Pre-wash jeans, and keep fabric damp. 2️⃣ Fill a large pot with hot water, 1 cup of salt, and 1 teaspoon of dish soap. There must be enough water to fully submerge the jeans and stir them easily. 3️⃣ Put on rubber gloves, and shake dye bottle well. Add half a bottle of Rit All Purpose Dye in Lemon Yellow to pot. 4️⃣ Place pot on stovetop, and set to medium heat. 5️⃣ Add jeans to dye bath. Stir jeans constantly for 30 minutes and make sure all areas of the fabric get submerged evenly. Use tongs to help separate any folds in the fabric. 6️⃣ To lock in your color and reduce bleeding, use RIT ColorStay Dye fixative. Fill a sink or bucket with 3 gallons of hot water and add half a bottle of the Dye Fixative. Move jeans immediately from the dye bath to the prepared Dye Fixative bath. Stir jeans for 20 minutes. 7️⃣ Rinse jeans in sink with cool water until water runs clear. 8️⃣ Wash jeans by hand or washing machine (by themselves) with mild detergent and warm water.  #ritdye #upcycle #thriftflip #fabricdyeing #reworkedclothing

Don’t try to cook 4+ cups of rice on the stove using the absorption method, you’ll end up with a mushy layer at the bottom of the pot. Bake it. So easy, totally hands off, works every time. Do 2 pans at the same time for big big batch! - N x ❤️ PS rice to water ratio for oven is 1:1.5 for 2 cups rice then drops to 1:1 for 4+ cups rice (in CUPS not weight/L, 1c basmati = 190g, 1c water =250g) BIG BATCH FLUFFY BAKED BASMATI RICE (Also works for long grain, see notes) Use a 23 x 33 x 6 cm metal pan (13 x 9”) 4 cups basmati rice (750g), not washed* (serves 12 - 14) 4 cups (1 litre) boiling water OR: 6 cups / 1.2kg basmati rice, not washed* (serves 15 - 18) 6 cups / 1.5L boiling water 1. Preheat oven to 200C/390F (180C fan) 2. Put rice and boiling water in pan. Spread rice out evenly (work quickly), cover tightly with foil. 3. Bake 35 minutes for 4 cups rice, 45 min for 6 cups. Remove from oven, rest 10 minutes - do not remove the foil! 4. Fluff gently, serve.  * rice rinsing not necessary for fluffy rice or cleaning if you buy in packets where rice is cleaned before packaging (I’m in Australia) BUT if you buy rice from sacks off the street it is best to wash, do not soak, drain well then reduce boiling water by 1/3 cup to account for water logged in rice (2T for 2 cups rice). Notes - Can also use long grain rice. Recipe is different for jasmine, brown and sushi rice. - For 2 cups of rice, use a 20cm/8” square pan with 3 cups boiling water, 35 min same temp. - Frozen rice is a life staple. Cool, freeze, microwave from frozen (sprinkle with bit of water if needed to make it a bit steamy if it seems a bit dry). #recipetineats #howtocookrice

Ghooreh Mosamma Gilani  is a chicken and eggplant stew cooked with unripe grapes and Verjuic. It’s a delicious meal enjoyed mostly in the northern parts of Iran.  Ingredients (serves 3-4): - 3 chicken legs - 1 large onion - 2 tablespoons tomato paste  - 1/2 teaspoon salt - 1/2 teaspoon turmeric  - 1/3 teaspoon black pepper  - 1/3 teaspoon garlic powder  - 1/2 teaspoon cinnamon powder  - 2 tablespoons liquid saffron  - 3 cups of boiling water - 4 tablespoons Ghooreh (unripe grapes) - 2 tablespoons Verjuice  - 6-8 small eggplants (2 per person) - 6-8 small tomatoes (2 per person) Instructions:  - Wash and pat dry chicken legs. In a large pan, add the chicken legs, tgen sprinkle salt, turmeric and black pepper on top of them. Fry each side till golden brown. Remive the chicken legs from the pan.  - Add the grated onion to the pan with leftover oil, stir it for a couple of minutes. Then add tomato paste, garlic powder and cinnamon powder. Mix and stir for a minute or so. Put the chicken legs back into the pa, and pour some liquid saffron on them. Cover and cook on low for an hour.  - Meanwhile, wash and peel the eggplants. Then fry them in a pan till all sides are completely browned. Add the fried eggplants to the chicken pot. Next, add Ghooreh and Verjuice to the pot. Cover and cook on low for 10 minutes.  - Fry some small tomatoes in the same pan you used for frying the eggplants for a couple of minutes. Then add them to the chicken pot. Adjust the salt of the stew and add more salt if needed. Cover and cook on low for another 10 minutes. And done ✅  Chelo with bread tahdig Ingredients: - 2-3 cups rice - 1 tablespoon salt - 1 large tortilla cut into triangles  - 4 tablepoons olive oil  To make the rice, wash rice 3 to 4 times with cold water. Let it soak in some salted water for an hour. Then add rice to a pot of boiling water. Cook on high for 6-8 minutes until rice is 80% cooked. Drain the rice and set aside. Add some olive oil to the pot. Cover the bottom of the pot with bread pieces. Add rice on top. Cover and cook on low for 45 -60 minutes.  Serve this amazing dish with herbs, pickles and salad Shirazi. STOP THE DAMN MADNESS! For those of y’all tired of hearing me talk about Western North Carolina, buckle up because I’m not stopping. This is my home. Take a look at Old Fort Elementary—it looks okay from the outside, but the restoration trucks tell the real story. Thank you, Belfor, for stepping up to help save that school. Now, look at this house. The waterline is so high the windows are busted out. This neighbor is fighting to save a brick house, and behind it, a trailer got washed up and dumped right there. Debris is everywhere. It’s two months after Hurricane Helene—and it still looks like a war zone. Cleanup takes contractors, resources, and yes, money. But here’s the kicker. While small towns like Old Fort struggle, I discovered that North Carolina allocated $5M+ for security at an immigrant housing center in Greensboro, with $22M more planned. Meanwhile, we’re told there’s no money to help folks who’ve paid into the system for years. To the bureaucrats and elected officials: Do better. Reallocate those funds to the people of North Carolina who need it to rebuild their schools, homes, and communities. Let’s help our neighbors stay where they belong—in the communities they love. Stop wasting taxpayer dollars on nonsense and start prioritizing the people who earned them. Learn how to help:  https://patriotrelief.company.site/products/donation #leighbrown #onecommunity #HurricaneHelene #WesternNCStrong #OldFortNC #DoBetter #RebuildNC
