Pour stations are in theory a great idea. I've never understood why every place doesn't have them. If you think about it, a large place like Disneyland probably has dozens of huge trash compactors and pays per pound for their waste and recycling services. If I had to guess I would say they spend upwards of $100,000/month on their hauling services. Liquids and ice weigh a lot, so pouring them out could save thousands of dollars per month on disposal costs. And, liquids often contaminate recyclables, so any effort to drain them first would lead to cleaner, more recyclable materials. 

Disneyland has beautiful trash and recycling cans throughout the park, most of which are paired together, but the signage isn't particularly helpful:

PLASTIC - CANS - PAPER - GLASS (Does the park sell any glass items? Probably not)

People don't care about what they can recycle at home when they are out. There is a huge missed opportunity to  label these receptacles with the actual materials generated at the park. Keep it simple!

Water bottles, soda cans, and MAYBE clean and empty plastic cups that are made from PET #1 or PP #5. If we are being honest, that's it!

The pour station was a good idea, if they were using it properly. Instead, IF anyone pours out their liquids before recycling their bottles, they are literally just dumping it into the same trash bad! WTH?! I don't think they intended for this to be #greenwashing, but it is! 

If you've never heard of greenwashing, it is essentially misrepresenting something as environmentally friendly that is not. 

The Mouse can do better!

On January 25, 1998, Tom and Eileen Lonergan, an American couple and Peace Corps veterans, joined a group dive at St. Crispin’s Reef in Australia’s Great Barrier Reef.

After their final dive, the boat departed with 26 divers onboard.

But no one realized Tom and Eileen were still in the water.

A simple headcount error stranded them miles from shore.

It wasn’t until two days later that their bags were found on the boat — untouched.

Then came a chilling discovery: a dive slate reading, “Monday Jan 26, 1998 08am… Please help us before we die.”

Wetsuit fragments, tanks, and gear eventually washed ashore — but their bodies were never found.

Authorities concluded they likely drowned or were taken by sharks, but some speculate other possibilities.

Their story inspired books and the film Open Water.

A single oversight turned paradise into a silent death sentence — lost at sea, with no one left to hear them scream. #creepy #scary #truecrime #fyp #viral #sharks

**Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl**

Get ready for a flavor explosion with this incredible Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl! Perfect for a cozy night in or impressing your guests, this dish is a vibrant and mouthwatering experience you won't forget.

**Ingredients:**

- 1 1/2 lbs chicken breast
- 3 cups flour
- Peanut oil (for frying)
- 1/2 cup corn starch
- 1 red bell pepper, diced
- 1 can of chickpeas, rinsed and drained
- 1 can of black beans, rinsed and drained
- 1 can of red kidney beans, rinsed and drained
- 1 red onion, finely diced
- 1 cucumber, diced (peeling is optional)
- 1 cup bulgur, cooked to perfection
- 1 cup couscous, cooked and fluffy
- Green onion for a fresh garnish
- Lime wedges for that zesty kick

**Hot Honey Sweet Chili Sauce:**

- 1 Tbsp minced garlic
- 2 Tbsp minced yellow onion
- 1/2 stick of unsalted butter
- 3 1/2 Tbsp raw honey
- 1/4 cup sweet chili sauce
- 3 Tbsp Frank’s Hot Sauce
- 1 Tbsp sriracha
- 1 tsp onion powder
- 1/2 tsp garlic powder
- 2 Tbsp rice wine vinegar
- Salt and pepper to taste

**Let’s Get Cooking!**

Kick things off by infusing your chicken breast with an array of vibrant flavors! Season it generously with chili powder, garlic powder, onion powder, paprika, cracked pepper, and a sprinkle of sea salt. A splash of avocado oil and a dollop of Greek yogurt will ensure your chicken stays juicy and delicious as it marinates in this flavor bomb!

Next, create a fabulous egg wash and mix your seasoned flour to coat that chicken. The flour should be a reflection of all those delectable spices we just added!

Heat that peanut oil to a sizzling 175 degrees Fahrenheit and watch the magic happen as you dredge your chicken in the egg wash, then in your seasoned flour before frying until it’s golden brown and perfectly crispy.

While the chicken is frying to perfection, let’s prep the colorful medley of beans and veggies! Open those cans, give them a rinse, and let them drain, then chop up that red bell pepper, red onion, cucumber, and get those vibrant green onions ready for garnish.

Now for the pièce de résistance: take those juicy, crispy chicken pieces and toss them in your homemade hot honey sauce! 

Assemble your bowl with layers of flavor, showcasing each ingredient beautifully. Finally, drizzle that mouthwatering hot honey sauce all over your creation, topping it off with a sprinkle of green onion and fresh lime wedges to elevate the taste and appeal.

Your sensational Hot Honey Sweet Chili Chicken Bowl is ready to devour! Enjoy every bite!                                                 #food #fyppppppppppppppppppppppp

Many people believe that washing raw chicken before cooking is a necessary step to remove bacteria and ensure food safety. However, numerous food safety experts and health organizations, including the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) and the National Health Service (NHS) in the UK, advise against this practice. Contrary to popular belief, washing raw chicken can actually increase the risk of foodborne illness and spread harmful bacteria around the kitchen. Raw chicken often harbors potentially dangerous bacteria such as Salmonella and Campylobacter. When chicken is washed under running water, these bacteria can be splashed onto nearby surfaces, utensils, and even the cook, contaminating the kitchen and increasing the risk of cross-contamination. This can lead to the spread of foodborne illnesses, which can cause symptoms such as diarrhea, vomiting, and abdominal pain, and can be particularly dangerous for individuals with weakened immune systems, such as the elderly, young children, and those with chronic illnesses. Cooking chicken to the correct internal temperature of 165°F (74°C) is the most effective way to kill harmful bacteria. When chicken is cooked properly, any bacteria present on the surface or inside the meat will be destroyed, rendering the meat safe to eat. In contrast, washing raw chicken does not effectively remove or kill bacteria, and may even spread them further.  #healthandwellness #hygiene #healthyfood #healthylifestyle

Heatwave Alert: Take Care of Each Other 

As the National Heatwave Plan is activated in the Netherlands, remember: heat is deadly for the most vulnerable—the elderly, chronically ill, and young children. Check in on them. Hydrate. Avoid heat exposure.

But while citizens are asked to be responsible…

 The Netherlands remains a tax haven for multinationals dodging their dues.
 Tata Steel has been found dumping toxic chemicals in our waters.
⚠️ We only have 33 compliance officers to enforce worker and environmental safety.
 And now—don’t swim to cool off. Waters are contaminated with bacteria and heavy metals.

The government preaches “trickle-down economics” while the public pays the price—with our health, our safety, and our future.

Let’s protect each other. But let’s also demand accountability.
